            <li>
                <label for="question1">What is Statistics and its relationship with other disciplines. Difference between Descriptive and Inferential Statistics.</label>
            </li>
   Statistics is the mathematical science involving the collection, analysis, and interpretation of data³. It has a vital relationship with various disciplines:

   - Economics: Statistics plays a crucial role in economics. It is used in various parts of economics like demand, supply, wages, interest, prices, profits, rents savings, investments, unemployment etc. Various laws such as law of consumption, of returns or distribution of incomes and profits are often used in Economics¹.
   - Planning: Planning is mainly a part of economics. We have to make different planning for different components for different periods. In almost all the spheres, whether those are individual, joint or any government decisions, nothing can be done without success and success cannot be attained without planning and planning cannot be undertaken without statistics¹.
   - Business and Commerce: These activities such as trading, manufacturing, banking, transportation, mining, insurance or such other activities are undertaken for making profits. Statistics helps us to a great extent in planning, analysing and executing the plans¹.
   - State Administration: Various departments of a government use it for their benefits and proper success of the departments held¹.
   - Other fields include Actuarial science, Astrostatistics, Biostatistics, Business analytics, Chemometrics, Demography, Econometrics, Environmental statistics, Epidemiology, Forensic statistics, Spatial statistics Geostatistics, Jurimetrics, Machine learning and Operations research².

   The difference between Descriptive and Inferential Statistics is as follows:

   - Descriptive Statistics: This branch aims to describe a chunk of raw data using summary statistics, graphs, and tables. Descriptive statistics are useful because they allow you to understand a group of data much more quickly and easily compared to just staring at rows and rows of raw data values⁴. Descriptive statistics describe a sample. You simply take a group that you’re interested in, record data about the group members, and then use summary statistics and graphs to present the group properties⁵.
   - Inferential Statistics: Inferential statistics allow scientists to take findings from a sample group and generalize them to a larger population⁶. Inferential statistics makes inferences about a larger population⁵.

