            <li>
                <label for="question2">Describe the concepts of Population, Sample Attribute, Variable, Level of measurement and Dataset.</label>
            </li>
1) Population: In statistics, a population is the complete set of items from which a statistical sample is drawn for a study¹. It can be a group of individuals, a set of items, etc. It makes up the data pool for a study⁴.
2) Sample: A sample refers to a smaller, manageable version of a larger group. It is a subset containing the characteristics of a larger population⁵. Samples are used in statistical testing when population sizes are too large for the test to include all possible members or observations⁵.
3) Attribute: In data analysis or data mining, an attribute is a characteristic or feature that is measured for each observation (record) and can vary from one observation to another[^10^]. It might be measured in continuous values (e.g., time spent on a website), or in categorical values (e.g., red, yellow, green)[^10^].
4) Variable: In statistical research, a variable is defined as an attribute of an object of study¹³. Choosing which variables to measure is central to good experimental design¹³. A variable is any characteristic, number, or quantity that can be measured or counted¹⁶.
5) Level of Measurement: There are four levels of measurement: nominal, ordinal, interval and ratio. The level of measurement can influence the choice of statistical methods used to analyze the data, as some methods may be more appropriate for certain types of data than others¹⁷.
6) Dataset: A dataset (or data set) is a collection of data. In the case of tabular data, a dataset corresponds to one or more database tables, where every column of a table represents a particular variable, and each row corresponds to a given record of the dataset in question²². The dataset lists values for each of the variables for each member of the dataset²².

