            <li>
                <label for="question4">Briefly describe the main experiment designs</label>
                
            </li>
1) Pre-experimental Research Design: This is the simplest form of experimental research design. It is often used to test the effects of a treatment on a group³.
2) True-experimental Research Design: This is the most accurate form of experimental research design as it relies on the statistical hypothesis to prove or disprove the hypothesis³.
3) Quasi-Experimental Design: This type of design does not randomly assign subjects to treatment and control groups, making it less reliable for establishing cause-and-effect relationships³.
4) Randomised Block Design: This design is used when the experimenter wishes to control the variation in an experiment that is related to differences in test units³.
5) Completely Randomised Design: In this design, all experimental units have an equal chance of receiving any treatment³.
6) Between-Subjects Designs: In a between-subjects design, the various experimental treatments are given to different groups of subjects¹.
7) Factorial Design: An experiment might have just one independent variable or it might have several. This section describes basic experimental designs and their advantages and disadvantages¹.

Each design has its own strengths and weaknesses, and the choice of which to use will depend on the specific circumstances of the research.

